76561198365236399,Not Recommended,399790,30254163,Posted: 28 February,all,Awai,"I saw the reviews and I still ended up trying the game... ugh. Lots to cover and much to agree on with others.The game description states an epic 12 hr JRPG and being a lover of RPG, I bought it via a bundle to try. Continued reading the description and yes, the plot is just like a familiar and famous ninja manga. The story plot is essentially large chunks of the ninja manga and that is just unfortunate. I feel the game could have had a much more interesting story than doing a spin-off. Next thing you notice as you start the game, is the english dialogue. This is either aimed towards a much younger crowd where the people either find cursing amusing/to be giggled at (oh my goodness, did that character just say that!) or the developers actually thought people would like such type of dialogues. My opinion: no. De-values the game and detracts from the game as well - too many errors in the dialogue. If you are even remotely a grammar nut, you will cringle throughout the game when the characters 'talk'. Next, the 'travelling' aspect of the game. There truly isn't much space to travel. The storyline is so rigid that you can't possibly deviate it, skip it, or come back to it at all. IE: you don't want to progress in the game, but want to explore the town/buy items/etc. More often than you want, you can't do it, because when you try to enter the store, your character may say 'I don't have time to do this, I have to meet ... blah'. To me, that detracts from RPGs I'm used and maybe someone likes it, but I hated it. I understand the need to progress the storyline and all, but severely limiting what a character can do in-between the plot is just aggravating to the player. Next, 'world map'. No such thing. You can't travel freely 90% of the time. Again, it's all limited depending on your progression in the story plot. Next, battle system! The game teaches you how to initiate, avoid, and fight. It's nice how they did it and through the game, I liked the battle design until a certain point. My gripe with the system is not how the battle system is made, but the balance behind the battles. Your characters learn new skills and techniques (xtu as they are called) as they level up (great stuff right? No need to find skill books or etc), their cost of using each skill or technique goes up. One skill can cost 100 and the next skill learned that is suppose to be the next level of the skill is 200. The amount of damage from the skill costing 200 does less damage than the skill that costs 100. That is ridiculous! Other similar things: 1) A skill says the ultimate skill, does 1 damage to the enemy, but a skill that you started the game with does at least 20 damage (WTF), 2) an enemy is clearly resistant to fire damage, but only to certain fire xtu - fire wall doesn't work well, but fire storm does (WTF), 3) the skill list is not organized for each character, 4) your xtu techniques doesn't get that much stronger as your character's level get stronger/you equip better weapons (IE: fireball deals 100 dmg at the beginning of the game, deals roughly the same when I maxed out the character's level with a much better equip), 5) TP reset - like mana, but they get reset out of each battle, which is aggravating because some skills need 100 TP for activation, but you have to either use an item or wait a round or two to reach 100 TP to even use it, at which point you will realize you will die before you reach 100 TP via a regular way. 6) xtu states randomly attacks 2 enemies, I use it and it ONLY attacks the enemy ONCE - the game is full of glitchs. Even aside from all those points, the most aggravating part of the game that made me stop playing (even though I bared with it all till almost the end of the game) is the balance between the enemies you fight and your character leveling up. Enemies in the game are progressive, meaning as you level up, they level up accordingly. You will notice it as you get stronger in the first part of the game. While this made me think the game is pretty cool to do it, it is broken. Once you reach your level cap - lvl 50, you will realize you are fighting eneies that are 1) higher level AND 2) above your combat statistics' capabilities (because the game was designed to have progressive enemies that will always be higher than you). IE: in a boss fight, there is the boss character and 3 henchmen. The boss character is WEAKER than the henchmen, because the henchmen follows the progressive enemy mechanism more than the boss. While you may think better equips, playing defensively, trying different strategies would work in the end, I assure you, it does not. There are items in the game where you can boost your character's stats. I bought LOADS of them to pump my characters up. The enemies just get stronger based on your stats. At this point, after the carnival part of the story plot, I am facing 4 enemies that are faster than me, deals approx an average of 1K~2K dmg per attack from each enemy, while my characters are max level, has the best equip they can get at that point in the game, exceedingly boosted, and their skills synergizes well with each other. I COULD NOT get past that battle for the longest time. I have died within 3 rounds of battle where the first round I'm attacking and the next two rounds I'm trying to survive, but fail each time. It's near impossible based on the progressive enemy mechanism. After a whole day of trying, I only got past it due to RNG - random number generator - on status afflictions. I got lucky and the enemies were stunned, paralyzed, or frozen. That was the only way I could think of to pass the battle. Which apparently, is the end of the game, because it states 'To B continued'. Yes, the game states B instead of BE.Other things: the game tries to be funny and nonchalant about breaking the 4th wall in the game. No, that just proves how lacking the game was designed. This game can't even hold up a match to Deadpool's capabilities in breaking the 4th wall. The game also limits your ability to buy certain healing items as the game progress. IE: can't buy a potion that heals 25% of max hp, but you must buy the 50% one now. Minor thing, but not cost-effective in cases where I only want to recover 25%, but I have to use a 75% potion to do it as I can't buy the other one anymore. Gaining money can also be an issue in this game. You can get loaded with gold easily if you choose to get the accessory (lucky coin) and fight/grind in the game when there are monsters to fight. However, getting the money does almost nothing, but for you to buy healing items. Getting better equips can be argued to be a pro, but NOTE, this brings difficulties with the mechanism where enemies get stronger than you consistently as you grind/equip better items. At the carnival stage, there are some awesome armor and weapons to buy, but cost a lot. I was able to afford it, but because the stats on those items are so great, my enemies are THAT much stronger as well.Overall, I played game for approx 14 hours with 4 hours of it being trying again and again to pass a battle via RNG and status afflictions. There are definitely multiple flaws in this game where I would not recommend others to play it. It's an aggravating game to play with all those flaws and even more so if you can't win a battle, because you are doing so well in the game due to the imbalanced design. If you want to play this game, you have been warned. 2/10 from me.I just noticed, I have one achievement left - reach part 2. I started on normal mode and I don't know if the hard mode is where part 2 comes in, but I am not replaying this game to find out."
