,Not Recommended,399790,30161637,Posted: 25 February,all,nujumkey,"I'm rating this as negative, but really i want to give it a 5/10.Some of what's positive about this game can be found in other RPG maker games. Solid combat system, weapon/armor customization, story focus, linear gameplay. There's also a decent amount exploration for optional quests, and chests are plentiful. I can respect the effort to try and make the story themed around ninjas to get away from the generic medieval rpg maker game (though i will explain an issue with this later). It's also interesting to see the author experiment with a skill mechanic with the tp resource as i don't normally see RPG maker games use anything other than mana.Where this game looses points is in the writing. As an rpg maker game, you're writing is like %50 of the reason why people will pick up your game, so here are some notes about this games writing.-The game tries very hard to explain things very clearly, which leads to a ton of extra text that doesn't feel like it's doing anything. For example the phrase ""speaking in a soft voice"" wasn't necessary because the characters dialog already had gaps and stutters in it.-Thematically you're supposed to be a ninja in training, but the scenery you're in and the people you interact with aren't really themed appropriately. This is of course, an issue with making a game with RPG maker as there is a limited amount of sprites and textures provided to you, but that isn't an excuse for how jarring it is to see a knight is heavy armor in ninja academy.-The plot itself was alright, until i realized that huge chunks of it were ripped-off of young naruto's story. Finally watching anime pays off!-I never thought i'd say this, but the grammer bugged me. So many sentences just felt akward; I'm not good at mechanical writing in general so i can't explain why but half the dialog doesn't work out in my head cleanly. Normally weak writing isn't an issue for me, but for RPG's where a huge part of the investment is the story, it sucks and really drains the enjoyment out of what's supposed to be an interesting part of the game.There is also a major issue with the abilities in the game, they are incredibly unsatisfying to use. Almost none of the mana based abilities do more than you basic attack, so the only reason to use your abilities is to either deal AOE (area of effect) damage, deal a specific elemental damage, or to heal.Some minor notes: there is achievement for beating the character Zane in training, however you train with the guy twice. When you beat him the first time you don't get the achievement, which made me think the game was broken. Some clarification on that would be nice. Also i would like it if i had a chance to buy equipment with the party members i'm going to use, so i'm not having to guess what equipment they can use.Ultimately i found myself liking the game, but i suspect that's because i'm a sucker for straighforward RPG games with linear progression, not because the game was especially good. It's not to not need a walkthrough to get through the game for once. If you've played other RPG maker game you know what you're in for, maybe get it for the easy achievements but otherwise i'd avoid it."
