,Not Recommended,399790,20613527,"Posted: 18 January, 2016",all,Zephadus,"Okay, so as someone who has tinkered with RPG Maker for years, I'm trying to cut this game a little slack, especially since it almost exclusively uses the pre-supplied resources, save for a sideview battle system and various edits of the base character graphics.I can deal with that, and I can see why it was done. However...The dialogue drives me up the wall.Several words are misspelled, punctuation seems random, and the game can't decide between ""X-tu"" and ""xtu"".Also, the obscene amount of exclamation points and question marks used is just obnoxious.And before I even get to move or look at anything, the game wants to tell me the controls, and that I can press F1 for options (including remapping the controls it just told me about) and F5 for fullscreen/window toggle.The game immediately tells you about the ninja village you live in, the Kage that sacrificed himself, the sealing of beasts inside of children, the village in the leaves, and then you go to school to meet your friends, the emo kid, the healer, and the one nobody cares about, and your first mission is to retrieve some bells from your sensei.After that, it's revealed that Orochimaru, a ninja master long thought dead, is actually alive, and is......Wait, no, sorry, I got lost there for a moment. I thought I was writing a review for a JRPG, not Naruto.You'd be forgiven for thinking they're the same thing.Also, before you see any real action, there is actually a battle tutorial.It teaches you the complex art of battle, covering topics such as ""how to attack"", which tells you about the attack button, and how to press it; ""hp and you"", which teaches you the fundamentals of health points (or sometimes hit points); ""skills for the skilled"", which covers everything you need to know about selecting attacks that cost MP (I think it's MP anyway, I couldn't be bothered to commit any of this to memory).But yeah, a battle tutorial. For a JRPG. Yep.And just in case you forgot, you can press F1 for options, and F5 to switch between fullscreen and windowed.There are also save points, but those don't matter, because they forgot to disable saving anywhere you want.While this game has its flaws, it still did one good thing:it taught me that I can put very little effort into an RPG Maker game, and it will make a few bucks.You too can be the next big JRPG star! ...or at least make a few bucks on some shovelware. :)"
